Abstract
This project focuses on developing a supervised machine learning model to classify textual reviews or social media posts into sentiment categories: positive, negative, and neutral. Using TF-IDF vectorization for feature extraction and logistic regression as the classifier, the system analyzes raw text data to determine the underlying sentiment automatically. 
The project involves data pre-processing, model training, evaluation, and testing on unseen data to measure accuracy and performance. 
The solution aims to provide a scalable and efficient approach for sentiment analysis, which can be applied in domains such as customer feedback analysis, brand monitoring, and social media sentiment tracking. Future enhancements could include leveraging more advanced natural language processing techniques and deep learning models to improve accuracy and handle complex linguistic nuances.


Project Overview
This project develops a supervised machine learning model for sentiment classification of textual reviews or social media posts. 
It uses TF-IDF vectorization to convert text into numerical features and employs logistic regression to classify sentiments into positive, negative, or neutral categories. The process involves data collection, pre-processing, model training on labeled datasets, and evaluation using metrics like accuracy and confusion matrix. 
The purpose is to automate sentiment analysis for applications such as customer feedback evaluation, brand monitoring, and social media insights. This approach can scale to large datasets and serves as a foundation for incorporating advanced NLP models to enhance sentiment detection accuracy and contextual understanding. 
The project aims to provide a usable sentiment prediction tool that demonstrates core concepts of natural language processing and supervised learning in machine learning


